    <h3>Calculus</h3>
    <ul>
    
    <li> <a href="/notes/inverse_functions"><div style="font-family: Roboto;font-size:14pt">Derivitive of Inverse Functions</div></a>
    <h2 id="the-thing">The Thing</h2>

<p>Take a function $f$, and let $g = f^{-1}$.  Then we can compute its derivative using:
\(f(g(x)) = x \\
\implies \dv{}{x}f(g(x)) = 1\\
\implies f'(g(x))g'(x) = 1\)
So that, remembering $g=f^{-1}$, we get:
\(\begin{equation}
\label{eq:inverse}
\boxed{g'(x) = \frac1{f\left(f^{-1}(x)\right)}.}
\end{equation}\)</p>

<h2 id="an-example">An Example</h2>

<p>You can use Eq. ($\ref{eq:inverse}$) this to work out the derivatives of the inverse trigonometric functions.   As an example:
\(\begin{align}
\dv{}{x}\arccos x &amp;= \frac1{-\sin(\arccos(x))}, \nonumber\\
&amp;= \frac{-1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}.
\end{align}\)</p>

    </li>

    
    </ul>


